# Close session

`C-x` closes the selected live tmux session without deleting any attached
workspace, then refreshes the session list without closing the app or resetting
the query.

    :bins jj tmux cat sleep

> [!NOTE]
> 'jj', 'tmux', 'cat', and 'sleep' are available.

    :t rename-session -t 0 runner (success)
    :t new-session -d -s alpha "cat" (success)
    :t new-session -d -s alpine "cat" (success)
    :t new-session -d -s ui "sesh; cat" (success)
    :t resize-window -t ui:0 -x 120 -y 14 (success)
    :pane ui:0.0
    :settle (settled)

Filter to the matching sessions. The first match, `alpha`, is selected.

    :k alp
    :snap

```terminal
session: alp
  2/4 | [C-r] repo: none | [C-x] close, [C-f] flag
   alp                                                                                                                 ┃
▌⬤ alpha                                                                                                               ┃
 ⬤ alpine                                                                                                              ┃
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────








```

Pressing `C-x` should kill `alpha`, keep `sesh` running, preserve the `alp`
query, and show the refreshed list with only `alpine` remaining.

    :k C-x
    :settle (settled)
    :snap

```terminal
session: alp
  1/3 | [C-r] repo: none | [C-x] close, [C-f] flag
   alp                                                                                                                 ┃
▌⬤ alpine                                                                                                              ┃
                                                                                                                       ┃
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────








```

    :t has-session -t alpha (failure)

```
can't find session: alpha
```

    :t has-session -t alpine (success)
    :t has-session -t ui (success)

